ubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven as life expectancy in many countries has continued to increase, social security and similar government programs can provide strong incentives for workers to leave the labor force when they reach the age of eligibility for benefits. Disability insurance programs can also play a significant role in the departure of older workers from the labor force, with many individuals in some countries relying on disability insurance until they are able to enter into full retirement. The sixth stage of an ongoing research project studying the relationship between social security programs and labor force participation, this volume draws on the work of an eminent group of international economists to consider the extent to which differences in labor force participation across countries are determined by the provisions of disability insurance programs. Presented in an easily comparable way, their research covers twelve countries, including Canada, Japan, and the United States, and considers the requirements of disability insurance programs, as well as other pathways to retirement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDisability retirement. 0aPostemployment benefits. 0aSocial security. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aDisability insurance.  aLabor force participation.  aRetirement incentives.1 aBanks, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehaghel, Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBingley, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanchet, Didier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrugiavini, Agar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat